{"title_page": "Women Airforce Service Pilots", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. Army Air Corps female auxiliary pilots}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP)\n| type = \n| seal = \n| seal_width = 250px\n| seal_caption = [[Fifinella]] unit [[mascot]] patch<ref name=\":6\" />\n| logo = File:WASPbadge.jpg\n| logo_width = 250px\n| logo_caption = The WASP badge\n| image = File:Elizabeth L. Remba Gardner, Women's Airforce Service Pilots, NARA-542191.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| image_caption = [[Elizabeth L. Gardner]], WASP member, at the controls of a [[B-26 Marauder]]\n| formed = {{Start date|1943|08|05}}\n| preceding1 = Women's Flying Training Detachment (WFTD), formed September 1942\n| preceding2 = Women's Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS), formed September 1942\n| dissolved = December 20, 1944\n| jurisdiction = \n| headquarters = \n| coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto = \n| employees = 1,830 accepted for training <br /> 1,074 completed training\n| budget = \n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency = [[United States Army Air Forces]]\n| agency_id = \n| website = \n| map = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = \n| footnotes = \n| embed = \n}}\n\nThe '''Women Airforce Service Pilots''' ('''WASP''') (also '''Women's Army Service Pilots'''<ref>\"Cornwall Postmaster Ferried Warplanes in World War II,\" The Evening News, Oct 8, 1971, page 3a; \"Women Pilots May Become Members of the Army Air Forces,\" The Reading Eagle, Nov. 1, 1943, page 20; \"Veterans Begin Aid Fight,\" The Age, May 25, 1977, page 20; \"Veterans Bill Advances,\" St. Petersburg Times, Nov. 4, 1977, page 3A; \"Women in the military,\" Sarasota Harold Tribune, May 26, 1995, 5B; \"Sunday's the Day for Washington Gals To Fly Somewhere for Breakfast,\" The Evening Independent, Jul. 31, 1947, page 6; \"War Prisoner's Wife Enters Flying Group,\" Prescott Evening Courier, Jun, 16, 1944, page 8; and \"Early Decision Pilots Her Through Life,\" Toledo Blade, Jan.10, 1975, page 10.</ref> or '''Women's Auxiliary Service Pilots'''<ref name=\":9\" />) was a [[civilian]] women pilots' organization, whose members were [[United States federal civil service]] employees. Members of WASP became trained pilots who tested aircraft, ferried aircraft, and trained other pilots. Their purpose was to free male pilots for combat roles during [[World War II]]. Despite various members of the armed forces being involved in the creation of the program, the WASP and its members had no military standing.\n\nWASP was preceded by the [[Women's Flying Training Detachment]] (WFTD) and the Women's Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS). Both were organized separately in September 1942. They were pioneering organizations of civilian women pilots, who were attached to the [[United States Army Air Forces]] to fly military aircraft during World War II. On August 5, 1943, the WFTD and WAFS merged to create the WASP organization.\n\nThe WASP arrangement with the US Army Air Forces ended on December 20, 1944. During its period of operation, each member's service had freed a male pilot for military combat or other duties. They flew over 60&nbsp;million miles; transported every type of military aircraft; towed targets for live anti-aircraft gun practice; simulated strafing missions and transported cargo. Thirty-eight WASP members lost their lives and one disappeared while on a ferry mission, her fate still unknown as of 2019.<ref name=\"Ulre\">{{cite book|last1=Ure|first1=James|title=Seized by the Sun: The Life and Disappearance of World War II Pilot Gertrude Tompkins|date=2017|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781613735909|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fvR_DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT158&lpg=PT158&dq=Gertrude+Tompkins+Silver#v=onepage&q=Gertrude%20Tompkins%20Silver&f=false|language=en}}</ref> In 1977, for their World War II service, the members were granted [[veteran]] status,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=124533914 |title=WWII Female Pilots Honored With Gold Medal |date=March 10, 2010 |work=All Things Considered |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> and in 2009 awarded the [[Congressional Gold Medal]].<ref name=\"gpo\">{{cite web|title=Women Airforce Service Pilots Congressional Gold Medal|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-111publ40/html/PLAW-111publ40.htm|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"thune.senate.gov\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thune.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/2009/5/press-release-026b5888-86e0-4688-a4fc-e9e680ea96e4|title=Thune Recognizes Women Airforce Service Pilots from World War II|last=|first=|date=May 21, 2009|work=United States Senator John Thune|accessdate=2013-07-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224124156/https://www.thune.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/2009/5/press-release-026b5888-86e0-4688-a4fc-e9e680ea96e4|archive-date=24 December 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Creation of the WASP==\nWASP started out as two separate organizations. Pilot [[Jacqueline Cochran|Jacqueline \"Jackie\" Cochran]] wrote to the First Lady, [[Eleanor Roosevelt]], in 1939 to suggest the idea of using women pilots in non-combat missions.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=111}}{{Sfn|Sage|2017|p=10-11}} Cochran was introduced by Roosevelt to General [[Henry H. Arnold]], chief of the [[United States Army Air Forces|Army Air Force]], and to General [[Robert Olds]], who became the head of the [[Air Transport Command]] (ATC).{{Sfn|Sage|2017|p=11}} Arnold asked her to ferry a [[bomber]] to [[Great Britain]] in order to generate publicity for the idea of women piloting military aircraft.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=111}} Cochran did go to England, where she volunteered for the [[Air Transport Auxiliary]] (ATA) and recruited American women pilots to help fly planes in Europe.<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/research/online_documents/jacqueline_cochran.html|title=Jacqueline Cochran and the Women's Airforce Service Pilots (WASPs)|website=Eisenhower Presidential Library|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111065452/https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/research/online_documents/jacqueline_cochran.html|archive-date=11 January 2019|url-status=|access-date=14 January 2019}}</ref> Twenty-five women volunteered for the ATA with Cochran.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=American Women Pilots|date=3 September 1943|publisher=United States Army|url=https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/research/online_documents/jacqueline_cochran/BinderJJ.pdf|last1=Cochran|first1=Jacqueline|access-date=16 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111110124/https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/research/online_documents/jacqueline_cochran/BinderJJ.pdf|archive-date=11 January 2019}}</ref> The American women who flew in the ATA were the first American women to fly military aircraft.<ref name=\"archives\" /> While in England, Cochran studied the organization of both the ATA and the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF).{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=126}}\n\nIn the summer of 1941, Cochran and test-pilot [[Nancy Harkness Love]] independently submitted proposals to the U.S. Army Air Forces to allow women pilots in non-combat missions after the outbreak of [[World War II]] in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertyletters.com/resources/pearl-harbor/women-ferrying-pilots.php|title=Women Ferrying Pilots&nbsp;\u2013 Requirements for Hiring&nbsp;\u2013 Pearl Harbor Filing Cabinet|date=September 15, 1942|publisher=Liberty Letters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105043407/http://www.libertyletters.com/resources/pearl-harbor/women-ferrying-pilots.php|archive-date=5 January 2019|url-status=|access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref> The plan was to free male pilots for combat roles by using qualified female pilots to ferry aircraft from the factories to military bases, and also to tow drones and aerial targets. The U.S. was building its air power and military presence in anticipation of direct involvement in the conflict, and had belatedly begun to drastically expand its men in uniform. This period led to the dramatic increase in activity for the [[U.S. Army Air Forces]], because of obvious gaps in \"manpower\" that could be filled by women. To compensate for the manpower demands of the military after the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]], the government encouraged women to enter the workforce to fill both industrial and service jobs supporting the war effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eagleton.rutgers.edu/research/americanhistory/ap_ww2-pearl.php#pearl|title=Pearl Harbor and Mobilization|website=Eagleton Institute of Politics|publisher=Rutgers University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517093957/http://www.eagleton.rutgers.edu:80/research/americanhistory/ap_ww2-pearl.php|archive-date=17 May 2016|url-status=}}</ref>{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=123-124}}\n\n===WAFS===\n[[File:Women's_Auxiliary_Ferrying_Squadron_pilots,_March_7,_1943.jpg|thumb|Women's Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS) pilots, March 7, 1943]]\nNancy Harkness Love's husband, Robert Love, was part of the Army Air Corps Reserve and worked for Colonel [[William H. Tunner]].{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=123-124}} When Robert Love mentioned that his wife was a pilot, Tunner became interested in whether she knew other women who were pilots.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=124}} Tunner and Nancy Love met and began to plan an aviation ferrying program involving women pilots.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=124}} More formally, on June 11, 1942, Colonel Tunner suggested putting women pilots into the [[Women's Army Corps|Women's Army Auxiliary Corps]] (WAAC).{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=73}} However, there were technical problems with this suggestion, so it was decided to pursue hiring civilian pilots for the ATC instead.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=73}} By June 18, Love had drafted a plan to send to General [[Harold L. George]] who sent the proposal onto General [[Henry H. Arnold]].{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=73}} [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] wrote about women working as pilots during the war in her September 1 \"My Day\" newspaper column, supporting the idea.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=75}} General George again broached the idea with General Arnold, who finally, on September 5, directed that \"immediate action be taken and the recruiting of women pilots begin within twenty-four hours.\"{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=76}} Nancy Harkness Love was to be the director of the group and she sent out 83 [[Telegraphy|telegrams]] to prospective women pilots that same day.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=76}}\n\nThe Women's Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS) went into operation publicly on September 10, 1942.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/women/history/pilots.html|title=Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP)|website=Women in the United States Army|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008183357/https://www.army.mil/women/history/pilots.html|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref>{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=77}} Soon, the Air Transport Command began using women to ferry planes from factory to airfields. Love started with 28 women pilots, but they grew in number during the war until there were several squadrons.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=2}} Requirements for recruits were that they had to be between ages 21 and 35, have a high school diploma, a commercial flying license, 200 horsepower engine rating, five-hundred hours of flight time and experience in flying across the country.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=124-125}}\n\nUniforms for the WAFS were designed by Love and consisted of a gray [[gabardine]] jacket with brass buttons and square shoulders.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=44}} The uniform could be worn with gored skirts or slacks also made of gabardine.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=44}} Because they had to pay for their own uniforms, only 40 women ever wore the WAFS uniform.<ref name=\":4\" /> All WAFS were issued a flight uniform of [[khaki]] flight coveralls, a [[parachute]], [[goggles]], a flying scarf and leather [[Flight jacket|flying jacket]] sporting the ATC patch.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=96}} Headquarters for WAFS was at [[New Castle Air National Guard Base|New Castle Army Air Base]].<ref name=\":4\" /> Tunner ensured that there were quarters for the women to live in at the base.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=74}} WAFS worked under a 90 day, renewable contract.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=43}} WAFS earned $250 a month and had to provide and pay for their own room and board.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27853421/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Women of the Wind|last=Haggerty|first=Gillian|date=1991-11-11|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-31|pages=1|via=Newspapers.com}} and {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27770025/the_palm_beach_post/|title=WWII Fliers Didn't Have Glamour Job|last=|first=|date=1991-11-11|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-31|pages=10|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe first group of WAFS recruits were known as the Originals.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=91}} [[Betty Gillies]] was the first woman to show up for training.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=91}} On October 6, Gillies was made an executive officer and second-in-command of the WAFS.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=95}} Gillies was familiar with [[Military parade|drill]] and command techniques which she had learned at finishing school.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=126}} The first WAFS assignment was run by Gillies on October 22, 1942.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=97}} Six WAFS would ferry six L-4B Cubs to the factory to Mitchel Field.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=97}} The original squadron of 28 was reduced to 27 when [[Aline Rhonie Hofheimer|Pat Rhonie]] left on December 31 after disagreeing with Colonel Baker.{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=97-98}}\n\nThe WAFS each had an average of about 1,400 flying hours and a commercial pilot rating. They received 30 days of orientation to learn Army paperwork and to fly by military regulations. Afterward, they were assigned to various ferrying commands.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.sarahbyrnrickman.com/books_originals.asp|title=The Originals&nbsp;\u2013 The Women's Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron of World War II|last=Rickman|first=Sarah Byrn|publisher=Disc-Us Books|year=2001|isbn=1-58444-263-8|location=Sarasota, FL}}</ref> At the beginning of 1943, three new squadrons were formed.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=37-38}} The 4th Ferrying Group was in [[Romulus, Michigan|Romulus]] and commanded by [[Adela Riek Schaar|Del Scharr]].{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=37-38}} The 5th Ferrying Group was stationed at [[Love Field, Dallas|Love Field]] and was under the command of [[Florene Miller Watson|Florene Miller]].{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=37-38}} The 6th Ferrying Group was stationed at [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] and commanded by [[Barbara Erickson London|Barbara Jane Erickson]].{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=37-38}}\n\n===WFTD===\nCochran returned from England and arrived in the US the day before the announcement of the WAFS.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=24-25}} Cochran was angry that Love's proposal had been accepted, while her own had seemingly been ignored.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=126}} The next day, Cochran flew to [[Washington, D.C.]] and confronted General Arnold about her earlier proposal.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=25}} The WAFS had been formed while General Arnold was out on prolonged medical leave.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=126}} On September 13, Arnold sent a memo to General [[George E. Stratemeyer]] that designated Cochran as the director of \"Women's Flying Training.\"{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=28}} On September 15, 1942, Cochran's training proposal was also adopted, forming the 319th [[Women's Flying Training Detachment]] (WFTD).{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=17}} WFTD would be working with the Flight Training Command (FTC).{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=82}} WFTD was conceived of a program to train more women to ferry aircraft.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=6}} On October 7, General Arnold proposed the goal of training 500 women pilots.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=50}} By November 3, General Arnold was proposing a \"maximum effort to train women pilots.\"{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=50}}\n\nThe Aviation Enterprises at Howard Hughes Field at the [[Houston Municipal Airport]] became the base of the WFTD.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=51}} The first trainees recruited for WFTD, class 43-1, started at [[Houston Municipal Airport]] on November 16, 1942.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=48}} Cochran made [[Dedie Deaton]] her staff executive and in charge of finding housing for class 43-1- also known as the \"Guinea Pigs.\"{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=51-52}}{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=59}} Women trained on old planes, many of which bore \"visible and invisible scars.\"{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=129-130}}\n\nWFTD pilots were issued large khaki coveralls (which the trainees called \"[[zoot suit]]s\"), were ordered to wear any shoes they had, and a [[hairnet]] on the flight line.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=56}} The WFTD women were housed in various locations and had to find their own transportation to training.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=62-63}} The first deaths occurred when Margaret Oldenburg and her instructor when they were practicing spins on March 7, 1943.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=130}} Oldenburg had put her plane, a [[Fairchild PT-19|PT-19]] open cockpit, into a spin that she could not recover from and the crash killed her and her instructor.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=130}} Because the WFTD were civilians, there was no money to cover the funeral costs.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=130}} Cochran paid for the expense out of her own pocket and Deaton escorted Oldenburg's body home.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=130}} Another crash took place on March 21, 1943, when [[Cornelia Fort]] was ferrying a BT-13 with a group of male pilots.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=131}} One of the pilots, while showing off, flew too close to Fort's plane and his landing gear collided with the wing of her plane, breaking part of it off.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=131-132}} The plane went into a nose-dive, killing her.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=132}}\n\nCochran pushed aggressively for a single entity to control the activity of all women pilots. Tunner, in particular, objected on the basis of differing qualification standards, and the absolute necessity of the ATC being able to control its own pilots. But Cochran's preeminence with Arnold prevailed, and in July 1943 he ordered the programs merged, with Cochran as director.<ref name=archives /> The WAFS and the WFTD were combined to form the Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26786533/the_journal_times/|title=WASPS Are Included in Army Air Force|last=|first=|date=|work=The Journal Times|access-date=2019-01-04|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Love continued with the program as executive in charge of WASP ferrying operations. The formal announcement combining WAFS and WFTD took place on August 20, 1943.{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=167}}\n\nWASP adopted a patch in 1943 that featured the female gremlin [[Fifinella]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airspacemag.com/daily-planet/fifinella-mischievous-gremlin-180951401/|title=The Roald Dahl Aviation Story that Disney Refused to Film|last=Maksel|first=Rebecca|date=22 May 2014|website=Air & Space Magazine|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125193614/https://www.airspacemag.com/daily-planet/fifinella-mischievous-gremlin-180951401/|archive-date=25 January 2018|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-16}}</ref> Fifinella was conceived by [[Roald Dahl]] and drawn by [[Walt Disney]], and became the official WASP mascot.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Requirements and demographics==\n[[File:Image-Hazel_Ying_Lee.jpg|thumb|[[Hazel Ying Lee]] in a Link trainer, 1944]]\nWASP adopted many of WAFS requirements, but added one other. Recruits still had to be between 21 and 35 years old, in good health, in possession of a pilot's license and 500 hours of flight time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26891393/wasp/|title=Female WASPS Flew Warplanes|last=|first=|date=23 February 1991|work=The Sentinel|access-date=2019-01-06|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Additionally, women were also required to be at least five feet and two inches tall.{{Sfn|Cole|1992|p=14, 16}} Over 25,000 women made application to join the WASP; 1,830 were accepted but only 1,074 completed the training.<ref name=\"Collins\" /> The applicants all had prior experience and airman certificates. Several WASPs had been trained previously in the [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veterantributes.org/TributeDetail.php?recordID=2225|title=Betty C.G.T. Blake|website=Veteran Tributes|publisher=Veteran Tributes, Gulfport, MS|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104124016/http://veterantributes.org/TributeDetail.php?recordID=2225|archive-date=4 January 2019|url-status=|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":04\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26813971/pittsburgh_postgazette/|title=WASP Put Sting in War Effort|last=Lash|first=Cindi|date=11 November 2002|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2019-01-03|via=Newspapers.com}} and {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26822518/pittsburgh_postgazette/|title=How the WASP Put a Sting in the War Effort|last=|first=|date=11 November 2002|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2019-01-03|page=A-6|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wai.org/pioneers/2006/betty-jane-bj-williams|title=Betty Jane \"BJ\" Williams|website=Women in Aviation International|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005195003/https://www.wai.org/pioneers/2006/betty-jane-bj-williams|archive-date=5 October 2018|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> Many women came from wealthy backgrounds or had husbands who helped pay for their expensive pilot training.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=133}} All WASP recruits were interested in serving their country.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=133}}\n\nAlthough the majority of WASPs pilots were white, they were not exclusively so. Two [[Chinese Americans]], [[Hazel Ying Lee]] and [[Maggie Gee (pilot)|Maggie Gee]], two women of [[Hispanic]] descent, [[Verneda Rodriguez]] and [[Frances Dias]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/oct/23/news/cl-40608|title=Adding a Missing Piece to Mosaic of American History|last=McLellan|first=Dennis|date=October 23, 2000|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"asian\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asiancemagazine.com/apr_2007/in_pursuit_of_a_dream|title=In Pursuit of a Dream|date=April 2007|publisher=Asiance Magazine|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302212326/http://www.asiancemagazine.com/apr_2007/in_pursuit_of_a_dream|archivedate=March 2, 2012|access-date=January 15, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/latinashistory/rodriguezmcleanverneda.html|title=RODR\u00cdGUEZ MCLEAN, VERNEDA (1918\u20131982)|last=|first=|date=|website=Latinas in History|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://histolines.wordpress.com/2019/02/10/wwii-wasp-female-pilot-frances-j-dias-in-her-yearbook-op-original-scan/|title=WWII WASP Female Pilot Frances J. Dias in her Yearbook \u2013 OP Original|last=|first=|date=10 February 2019|website=Making Histolines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> and one known [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] woman, [[Ola Mildred Rexroat]] completed the training. Rexroat was a member of the [[Oglala Sioux]] tribe from the [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]], in South Dakota.<ref name=\"Defense.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/specials/nativeamerican01/women.html|title=Native American Women Veterans|date=October 14, 2003|website=Native American Indian Heritage Month|publisher=Defense.gov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530122845/https://www.defense.gov/specials/nativeamerican01/women.html|archive-date=30 May 2010|url-status=|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref> While the number of black women applicants for WASP training is unknown, several black pilots made it to the final interview stage, where they were all rejected.{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=16}} [[Mildred Hemmons Carter|Mildred Hemmans Carter]], another [[African American]] applicant, was asked to withdraw her application because of her race. In 1940, at age 19, Carter had earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] Degree from the [[Tuskegee University|Tuskegee Institute]]. The following year, she received her aviation certification. However, because of her gender, Carter was also rejected from flying with the [[Tuskegee Airmen]]. Seventy years later, she was recognized retroactively as a WASP, and Carter took her final flight at age 90.{{Sfn|Dubois|Dumenil|2012|p=549}} Another black interviewee, [[Janet Bragg|Janet Harmon Bragg]], was told by Cochran that \"it was difficult enough fighting prejudice aimed at females without additionally battling race discrimination.\"{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=115}}\n\n==WASP training==\n[[File:43-3 Jan-1943.jpg|thumb|Start of WASP training&nbsp;\u2013 class of 43-3 in January 1943. Photo by Lois Hailey.]]\n[[File:WASPS-Women-Airforce-Service-Pilots-Training-1943-Army-Navy-Screen-Magazine-No.-16.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=02:16|Short film about the Women Airforce Service Pilots, part of the ''[[Army\u2013Navy Screen Magazine]]'' film series in 1943]]\nThe WASP training spanned 19 groups of women. The first group was the Originals, who were the first group of the Women's Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS), led by [[Nancy Harkness Love|Nancy Love]].{{Sfn|Rickman|2008|p=91}}\n\nThe second group was The Guinea Pigs which were [[Jacqueline Cochran|Jacqueline Cochran's]] first class of women pilots for the [[Women's Flying Training Detachment]] (WFTD).{{Sfn|Rickman|2016|p=59}} The Guinea Pigs started training at the Houston Municipal Airport (now [[William P. Hobby Airport]]) on November 16, 1942, as part of the 319th [[Women's Flying Training Detachment|Army Air Force Women's Flying Training Detachment]] (AAFWFTD). This was just after the WAFS had started their orientation in [[Wilmington, Delaware]]. Unlike the WAFS, the women that reported to [[Houston]] did not have uniforms and had to find their own lodging.{{Sfn|Cole|1992|p=13, 18}} The \"Woofteddies\" (WFTD) also had minimal medical care, no life insurance, crash truck, or fire truck, and the ambulance was loaned from the [[Ellington Field Joint Reserve Base|Ellington Army Airfield]], along with insufficient administrative staff, and a hodgepodge of aircraft\u201423 types\u2014for training.<ref name=\"Cole\" /> As late as January 1943, when the third class was about to start their training, the three classes were described by Byrd Granger in ''On Final Approach'', as \"a raggle-taggle crowd in a rainbow of rumpled clothing\", while they gathered for morning and evening colors.{{Sfn|Granger|1991|p=90}} There was also a lack of equipment, such as a [[Link Trainer|Link trainer]], that was necessary for training.{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=17}}\n\nThe first Houston class started with 38 women with a minimum of 200 hours. Twenty-three graduated on April 24, 1943, at the only Houston WASP graduation at Ellington Army Air Field. The second Houston class, started in December 1942 with a minimum of 100 hours, but finished their training just in time to move to [[Sweetwater, Texas]] and become the first graduating class from Avenger Field on May 28, 1943. The third class completed their advanced training at Avenger Field and graduated July 3, 1943. Half of the fourth class of 76 women started their primary training in Houston on February 15, 1943, and then transferred to Sweetwater. Later in the summer of 1943, both the WAFS and WFTD were combined into the WASP.{{Sfn|Granger|1991|p=70-121}} The first group to train as WASP started in Sweetwater on September 1943 and were designated as Class 44-W-2.{{Sfn|Cole|1992|p=7}}\n[[File:Avenger_Field_-_WASP_trainees_with_T-6_Texan.jpg|thumb|Avenger Field - WASP trainees with T-6 Texan]]\nEach WASP had a [[Pilot licensing and certification|pilot's license]], but was retrained to fly the Army way by the U.S. Army Air Forces at [[Avenger Field Airport|Avenger Field]] in Sweetwater, Texas.<ref name=\"Training\">{{cite web|url=https://twu.edu/library/womans-collection/featured-collections/women-airforce-service-pilots-wasp/training/|title=Training|website=Texas Woman's University|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728221611/https://twu.edu/library/womans-collection/featured-collections/women-airforce-service-pilots-wasp/training/|archive-date=28 July 2018|url-status=|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref> More than 25,000 women applied for the WASP, but only 1,830 were accepted into the program.<ref name=\"Collins\" /><ref>{{Cite archive|collection=Virginia Mae Hope Papers|institution=Minnesota Historical Society|item=Folder 1|item-url=http://www2.mnhs.org/library/findaids/p1549.xml|box=1}}</ref> During the course of their training, it was reported that 552 women were released for lack of flying proficiency, 152 resigned, 27 were discharged for medical reasons, and 14 were dismissed for disciplinary reasons.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Stewart-Smith|first=Natalie Jeanne|title=The Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP) Of World War II: Perspectives On The Work Of America's First Military Women Aviators|date=1981|publisher=Washington State University|chapter-url=http://home.earthlink.net/~reyesd99/stewartsmith/chapter2.html|chapter=2|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref> After completing four months of military flight training, 1,074 of them earned their wings and became the first women to fly American military aircraft. While the WASP were not trained for combat, their course of instruction was essentially the same as male aviation cadets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.megavision.net/wasp/Linkstwu/wardocreport.pdf|title=Director Of Women Pilots Asks Military Status For WASPS|last1=Cochran|first1=Jacqueline|date=1944|work=Press Release|accessdate=3 February 2018|publisher=War Department|agency=Bureau of Public Relations Press Branch}}</ref> They received no gunnery training and very little formation and aerobatic flying, but went through the maneuvers necessary to be able to recover from any position.<ref name=\"Life\">{{cite journal|date=19 July 1943|title=Girl Pilots|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MVAEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=Life Magazine|language=en|pages=73\u201381|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> The percentage of those eliminated compared favorably with the elimination rate for male cadets' in the [[Central Flying Training Command]].\n\nWASP recruits were required to complete the same primary, basic, and advanced training courses as male Army Air Corps pilots and many of them went on to specialized flight training.<ref name=\"thune.senate.gov\" /> They spent around 12 hours a day at the airfield with half the day spent practicing actual flight and the other half studying.<ref name=\"Training\" /> By graduation, WASP recruits had 560 hours of ground school and 210 hours of flight training.<ref name=\"Training\" /> They knew Morse code, meteorology, military law, physics, aircraft mechanics, navigation and other subjects.<ref name=\"Training\" />\n\n==Duties==\n[[File:Florene Watson in her P-51.jpg|thumb|Florene Watson shown preparing a [[P-51 Mustang|P-51D-5NA]] for a ferry flight from a factory at [[Inglewood, California]]]]\n\nAfter their training, the WASP were stationed at 122 air bases across the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wingsacrossamerica.us/wasp/baselist.htm|title=AAF Bases & Fields: WASP Duty Stations 1942-1944|website=WASP on the Web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924070828/http://wingsacrossamerica.us/wasp/baselist.htm|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref> where they assumed numerous flight-related missions, and relieved male pilots for combat duty.<ref name=\"test\">{{cite journal|last1=Pope|first1=Victoria|date=Spring 2009|title=Flight Of The Wasp|url=https://www.americanheritage.com/content/flight-wasp|journal=American Heritage|language=en|volume=59|issue=1|pages=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105042840/https://www.americanheritage.com/content/flight-wasp|archive-date=5 January 2019|via=}}</ref> Ferrying planes from factory to airbases made up the first duties of the WASP.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=102-103}} During [[World War II]], women pilots flew 80 percent of all ferrying missions.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=102}} They delivered over 12,000 aircraft.<ref name=\"Collins\" /> WASP freed around 900 male pilots for combat duty during World War II.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\nThe original WAFS were organized specifically to ferry airplanes and free male pilots for combat roles.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=103}} When a ferrying mission came in, the WASP would go to the factory, fly the plane in a test flight and then deliver the plane.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=102}} Between September 1942 and December 1944, the WASP delivered 12,652 aircraft{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=23}} of 78 different types. In order to set an example, Nancy Love who was in charge of training, made sure she was trained and qualified on as many different types of planes as was possible.{{Sfn|Sage|2017|p=13}}\n\nThey also towed targets for live anti-aircraft artillery practice, simulated strafing missions, and transported cargo. The live-target practice was announced by Jackie Cochran on July 19, 1943, to 25 recent WASP graduates at Avenger Field.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=132}} Cochran told the group that she had a \"top secret assignment\" and that any WASP could opt out if they wished: none did.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=132}} This group would be sent to [[Marine Corps Outlying Field Camp Davis|Camp Davis]] to tow flying shooting targets for men on the ground to practice shooting airborne targets.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=132}} Many of the planes were shot during this training and several WASP were shot in the feet.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=132-133}} Sometimes the planes were shot on purpose, when service men mistakenly believed they were supposed to shoot the plane, not the target the WASP was towing.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=104}} One of the planes used during target towing, an [[Douglas SBD Dauntless|A-24]] that, like many had not been adequately maintained by the Army Air Corps (AAC), killed WASP Mabel Virginia Rawlinson.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=135}} Rawlinson was practicing night flying with a trainer when her A-24 began to experience technical issues.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=135}} The instructor asked her to return to the airfield, but on the final approach, Rawlinson's plane connected with the top of a pine tree and the plane nosed down and crashed.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=135}} The instructor was thrown free, but Rawlinson was stuck in the front seat as the plane went up in flames, unable to open the plane's broken canopy lock.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=135}} The investigation into the crash and her death found that the towing planes were not maintained properly and the AAC was using the wrong [[octane]] fuel for the planes.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=135}}\n\nThe women flew almost every type of aircraft flown by the USAAF during World War II.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26760866/santa_maria_times/|title='Women of Courage,\" Takes Overdue Look at the Women Pilots of WWII|last=Dawson|first=Greg|date=31 May 1993|work=Santa Maria Times|access-date=2019-01-02|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In addition, a few exceptionally qualified women were allowed to test rocket-propelled planes, to pilot jet-propelled planes, and to work with radar-controlled targets. When men were less willing to fly certain difficult planes, such as the [[Bell P-59 Airacomet|YP-59]] and [[Boeing B-29 Superfortress|B-29 Super Fortress]], General Arnold recruited two WASPs to fly these aircraft.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=136-137}} Arnold believed that if men saw women fly these planes successfully, they would be \"embarrassed\" into taking these missions willingly.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=137}} Two WASPs, Dorthea Johnson and [[Dora Dougherty Strother]], were chosen to fly the B-29.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=136-137}} They flew to [[Alamogordo, New Mexico|Alamogordo]] in the B-29s where there was a crowd waiting to see them land.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=136-137}} General Arnold's plan worked, \"From that day on, there was no more grumbling from male pilots assigned to train on and fly the B-29 Super Fortress.\"{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=136-137}} Women would also test-fly the planes that had been repaired.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=102}}\n\nWhen not flying, the pilots studied [[navigation]], radio communications and new flying skills.{{Sfn|Smith-Daugherty|2012|p=102}}\n\nThirty-eight members lost their lives in accidents, eleven died during training, and twenty-seven were killed on active duty missions.<ref name= \"Collins\"/> Because they were not considered part of the military by the guidelines, a fallen WASP was sent home at family expense.<ref name= \"Dromgoole\"/> Traditional military honors or note of heroism, such as allowing the U.S. flag to be placed on the coffin or displaying a [[service flag]] in a window, were not allowed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/05/22/woman.pilots/|title=Unsung heroes of World War II finally get their due|last=Bohn|first=Kevin|date=May 22, 2009|work=CNN|access-date=17 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127203432/http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/05/22/woman.pilots/|archive-date=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Erdrich\"/><ref name= \"Dromgoole\"/>\n\n==Request for military status==\nThe WASP members were U.S. federal civil service employees, and did not qualify for military benefits.<ref name=archives /> Each member paid for her own transportation costs to training sites, for her dress uniforms and room and board.<ref name= \"Collins\"/> Although attached to the U.S. Army Air Forces, the members could resign at any time after completion of their training. On September 30, 1943, the first of the WASP militarization bills was introduced in the [[United States House of Representatives]] by Representative [[John M. Costello|John Costello]].{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=133}} Both Cochran and Arnold desired a separate corps headed by a woman colonel (similar to the [[Women's Army Corps|WAC]], [[WAVES]], [[SPARS]], and the [[United States Marine Corps Women's Reserve|Marine Corps Women's Reserve]] heads).<ref name=\"Treadwell\">{{cite book|last1=Treadwell|first1=Mattie E.|title=United States Army In World War II Special Studies The Womens Army Corps|date=1991|publisher=Center Of Military History United States Army Washington, D. C.|page=784|url=https://history.army.mil/books/wwii/Wac/appD.htm}}</ref> The War Department, however, consistently opposed the move, because there was no separate corps for male pilots as distinguished from [[United States Army Air Forces|unrated AAF officers]].<ref name=\"Treadwell\"/> In January 1944, Costello introduced a bill, HR 4219, to authorize women's commissions in the Army Air Forces.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=136}} General Arnold felt that there was room for women and men to work as pilots in the Army Air Forces.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=136}} He testified in front of the House military committee that the WASP were all \"good fliers and that he plans to send all the male pilots to fight.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27260144/the_pantagraph/|title=WASPS May Get Military Status|last=|first=|date=1944-03-23|work=The Pantagraph|access-date=2019-01-15|pages=1|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nHowever, some in the media disagreed with General Arnold and began to write opinion pieces in some of the most important media of the day.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=137}} ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'', The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' and the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' all urged women to step down and give the jobs back to men.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=137}} A journalist, [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]], questioned the legality of funding the WASP program, and even accused General Arnold of being manipulated by Jackie Cochran's \"feminine wiles\" in a ''[[Washington Times-Herald|Washington Times Herald]]'' column.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=137}} The column caused male civilian pilots to increase their efforts to write letters against the program.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=137}}\n\n==End of the WASP program==\n[[File:Curtiss A-25 tow target plane flown by a WASP.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Helen Wyatt Snapp|Helen W. Snapp]], flying for the Low-target Squadron, at [[Fort Stewart|Camp Stewart]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] June 1944]]\n\nOn June 21, 1944, the U.S. House bill to provide the WASP with military status, HR 4219, was narrowly defeated 188 against to 169 for.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=138}} The civilian male pilots lobbied against the bill: reacting to closure of some civilian flight training schools, and the termination of two male pilot training commissioning programs.<ref name = \"Airforce\"/> The House Committee on the Civil Service ([[Robert Ramspeck|Ramspeck]] Committee) reported on June 5, 1944, that it considered the WASP unnecessary, unjustifiably expensive, and recommended that the recruiting and training of inexperienced women pilots be halted.<ref name = \"Airforce\">{{cite news|title=Women's Airforce Service Pilots (WASP)|url=http://www.afhistory.af.mil/FAQs/Fact-Sheets/Article/458964/womens-airforce-service-pilots-wasp/|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=Air Force Historical Support Division|publisher=United States Air Force|date=December 8, 2011}}</ref> The committee had found that the program had cost $50 million in government funds.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=138}} Because of the cost, the program needed to request funding through legislation.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=138}}\n\nCochran had been pushing for a resolution of the question: in effect, delivering an ultimatum to either commission the women or disband the program.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=138}} The AAF had developed an excess of pilots and pilot candidates. As a result, Arnold (who had been a proponent of militarization) ordered that the WASP be disbanded by December 20, 1944.<ref name=archives /> Arnold is quoted from a speech he delivered at Avenger Field in Sweetwater, Texas on December 7, 1944:<ref name=\"Hazel\">{{cite book|last1=Hawkins|first1=Regina Trice|title=Hazel Jane Raines, Pioneer Lady of Flight|date=1996|publisher=Mercer University Press|isbn=9780865545328|page=135|url=https://books.google.com/?id=irPkbGhRLBEC&pg=PA135&lpg=PA135&dq=The+WASP+has+completed+its+mission.+Their+job+has+been+successful#v=onepage&q=%20WASP%20has%20completed%20its%20mission.%20Their%20job%20has%20been%20successful&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{quote\n|text=The WASP has completed its mission. Their job has been successful. But as is usual in war, the cost has been heavy. Thirty-eight WASP have died while helping their country move toward the moment of final victory. The Air Forces will long remember their service and their final sacrifice.\n}}\n\nOn December 7, 1944, the final class of WASP pilots, 71 women in total, graduated from their training regardless of the plan to disband the WASP program within the following two weeks.{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=124}} Following the announcement approximately 20 WASP members offered to continue ferrying aircraft for the compensation of {{US$|1.00|1944}} a year apiece but this offer was rejected.{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=120}} Before the WASP were disbanded, General Arnold ordered all commanding officers at bases where WASPs served, that the \"women pilots be issued a certificate similar to an [[Military discharge|honorable discharge]].\"{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=155}}\n\nFollowing the group's disbandment some WASP members were allowed to fly on board government aircraft from their former bases to the vicinity of their homes as long as room was available and no additional expenses were incurred. Others had to arrange and pay for their own transportation home.{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=126}} At the conclusion of the WASP program, 915 women pilots were on duty with the AAF: 620 assigned to the Training Command, 141 to the Air Transport Command, 133 to the numbered air forces in the continental United States, 11 to the Weather Wing, 9 to the technical commands and one to the Troop Carrier Command.<ref name=\"Cole\">{{cite book|last1=Cole|first1=Jean Hascall|last2=Cole|first2=Wendy|title=Women Pilots of World War II|date=1992|publisher=University of Utah Press|isbn=9780874804935|pages=13, 18|url=https://books.google.com/?id=od6hmG43CesC&pg=PR18&lpg=PR18&dq=WASP+Troop+Carrier+Command.#v=onepage&q=WASP%20Troop%20Carrier%20Command.&f=false|language=en}}</ref> The WASP members ferried fifty percent of the combat aircraft during the war to 126 bases across the United States.<ref name=\"Collins\" /> Because of the pioneering and the expertise they demonstrated in successfully flying military aircraft the WASP records showed that women pilots, when given the same training as men pilots, were as capable as men in non-combat flying.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stamberg|first1=Susan|title=Female WWII Pilots: The Original Fly Girls|url=https://www.npr.org/2010/03/09/123773525/female-wwii-pilots-the-original-fly-girls|author-link=Susan Stamberg|website=NPR|access-date=15 June 2017|quote='Now in 1944, it is on the record that women can fly as well as men,' Arnold said.}}</ref>\n\nDuring November 1944 WASP members at Maxwell Air Field founded the Order of Fifinella organization.<ref name=\":7\" /> The organization's initial goals were to help the former WASP members find employment and maintain contact between themselves.<ref name=\":7\" /> Through the years the Order of Fifinella issued newsletters, helped influence legislation and organized reunions.<ref name=\":7\" /> The group held its final meeting in 2008 and was disbanded in 2009.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://twu.edu/library/womans-collection/featured-collections/women-airforce-service-pilots-wasp/fifinella-wasp/|title=Order of Fifinella & WASP, Inc.|website=Texas Woman's University|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201192906/https://twu.edu/library/womans-collection/featured-collections/women-airforce-service-pilots-wasp/fifinella-wasp/|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany WASPs wanted to continue flying after they were disbanded.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27770087/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Ladies Courageous Flew Into Blue During WWII|last=O'Meilia|first=Tim|date=1976-10-02|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-29|pages=B1|via=Newspapers.com}} and {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27796712/the_palm_beach_post/|title=WASPs|last=|first=|date=1976-10-02|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-29|pages=B5|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[Airline|Commercial airlines]] turned women pilots away, \"saying public opinion wouldn't stand for it.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> WASP [[Teresa James]] wrote to congress requesting veteran's status.<ref name=\":42\" /> In order to keep flying, some women wrote [[Soong Mei-ling|Madame Chiang Kai-shek]] and volunteered for the [[Republic of China Air Force|Chinese Air Force]], who were still fighting against Japan.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27770062/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Memories of a Fly Girl|last=Kalajian|first=Douglas|date=1999-11-11|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-29|pages=1E}} and {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27797889/the_palm_beach_post/|title='Jamesy' Joins U.S. Air Force as a Reserve Flier in 1950|last=|first=|date=1999-11-11|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-29|pages=4E|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The [[United States Air Force]] offered commissions to former WASP in 1949, though all 121 who accepted the commissions were given support and administrative duties and did not fly.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Congressional_Gold_Medal_awarded_to_Women_Airforce_Service_Pilots.JPG |thumb|left|250px|Congressional Gold Medal awarded to WASPs]]\n[[File:WASP Congressional Gold Medal.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] signing the WASP [[Congressional Gold Medal]] bill into law]]\n\nThe records of the WASP program, like nearly all wartime files, were classified and sealed for 35 years making their contributions to the war effort little known and inaccessible to historians.<ref name=\"Erdrich\">{{cite news|url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2016/05/29/denial-military-honors-arlington-stings-wasps.html|title=Denial of Military Honors at Arlington Stings WASPs|last1=Erdrich|first1=Ronald W.|date=May 29, 2016|work=Military.com|accessdate=27 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130114446/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2016/05/29/denial-military-honors-arlington-stings-wasps.html|archive-date=30 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> However, there were unofficial historians, like WASP, [[Marty Wyall]], who collected [[Scrapbooking|scrapbooks]] and newspaper clipping about what the WASP members had done and what they had gone on to do.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26831605/the_indianapolis_star/|title=Fort Wayne Woman Keeps Female Fliers' Sagas Alive|last=Zweig|first=Beth Rosenberg|date=10 June 1990|work=The Indianapolis Star|access-date=2019-01-04|via=Newspapers.com}} and {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26831697/the_indianapolis_star/|title=Fliers|last=|first=|date=10 June 1990|work=The Indianapolis Star|access-date=2019-01-04|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Wyall also suggested in 1964, at a [[Ninety-Nines]] convention, that the remaining WASP members should meet up with one another every other year.<ref name=\":03\" />\n\nEarly efforts to gain recognition for the WASP continued in the early 1970s.<ref name=\":42\" /> There was support from the office of Senator [[Barry Goldwater]], who had flown with WASP during WWII.<ref name=\":42\" /> Goldwater's efforts to get the WASP veteran's status was met with shocking prejudice in Congress.<ref name=\":42\" /> According to Goldwater's legislative assistant, Terry Emerson, \"Women were treated as non-persons.\"<ref name=\":42\" /> In the House, Representative [[Patsy Mink]] introduced a bill on May 17, 1972, to give the WASP veterans status.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27769871/the_pittsburgh_press/|title=WASPs Ready for New Sting|last=Ross|first=Maddy|date=1972-06-27|work=The Pittsburgh Press|access-date=2019-01-31|pages=18|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Another representative in the House, [[Lindy Boggs]], introduced a bill around 1977 to give the WASP military status.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27864165/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Army's Promise to Women Pilots Never Honored|last=Wiggins|first=Ron|date=1977-09-11|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-31|pages=37|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975 under the leadership of Col. Bruce Arnold, the son of General Hap Arnold, along with the surviving WASP members organized as a group again and began what they called the \"Battle of Congress\". Their goal was to gain public support and have the WASP officially recognized as veterans of World War II.<ref name=\"PBS\" /> In 1976, there was a bill in the Senate Veteran's Affairs Committee to give the WASPs military status.<ref name=\":8\" /> The bill would allow WASP pilots to use veteran's services.<ref name=\":8\" /> In 1977, WASP records were unsealed after an Air Force press release erroneously stated the Air Force was training the first women to fly military aircraft for the U.S.<ref name=\"Erdrich\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Rudi|title=Defense.gov News Article: Women Aviators Finally Fill Cockpits of Military Aircraft|url=http://archive.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=29276|work=American Forces Press Service|publisher=archive.defense.gov|date=March 19, 2003|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite news|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/684700/wasps-were-pioneers-for-female-pilots-of-today-tomorrow/|title=WASPs Were Pioneers for Female Pilots of Today, Tomorrow|last1=Collins|first1=Shannon|date=March 2, 2016|work=DoD News Features, Defense Media Activity|access-date=17 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190118025148/https://dod.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/684700/wasps-were-pioneers-for-female-pilots-of-today-tomorrow/|archive-date=18 January 2019|publisher=U.S. Department Of Defense}}</ref><ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/flygirls-militarization-wasps/|title=Militarization of the WASPS|website=American Experience|publisher=PBS|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713171358/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/flygirls-militarization-wasps/|archive-date=13 July 2018|url-status=}}</ref> Documents were compiled that showed during their service WASP members were subject to military discipline, assigned top secret missions and many members were awarded service ribbons after their units were disbanded.<ref name=\"PBS\" /> It was also shown that WASP member Helen Porter had been issued a [[Military discharge#United States|Honorable Discharge certificate]] by her commanding officer following her service.<ref name=\"PBS\" />{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=155}} This time, the WASPs lobbied Congress with the important support of Goldwater, who himself had been a World War&nbsp;II ferry pilot in the 27th Ferrying Squadron.<ref name=\"Recognition\">{{cite news|last1=Collins|first1=Shannon|title=WASP Pursued Love of Flying, Fought for Women Vets' Recognition|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/689318/wasp-pursued-love-of-flying-fought-for-women-vets-recognition/|accessdate=27 January 2018|work=DoD News, Defense Media Activity|publisher=U.S. Department of Defense|date=March 9, 2016}}</ref> During hearings on the legislation opposition to the WASP members being given military recognition was voiced by the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Administration]] (VA), the [[American Legion]] and the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] (VFW).{{Sfn|Merryman|1998|p=150-152}} The VA, led by [[Dorothy L. Starbuck]], argued that WASP should not be given military recognition because the women were never subject to [[Court-martial|court martial]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The VFW felt that giving WASP military recognition would \"destroy the special status of veterans and do irreparable damage to veterans benefits.\"<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nPresident [[Jimmy Carter]] signed legislation, P.L.95\u2013202, Section 401, The G.I. Bill Improvement Act of 1977, providing that service as a WASP would be considered \"active duty\" for the purposes of programs administered by the Veterans Administration.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.8701 - An Act to amend title 38, United States Code to increase the rates of vocational rehabilitation, educational assistance and special training allowance paid to eligible veterans and persons, to make improvements in the educational assistance programs, and for other purposes.|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/95th-congress/house-bill/8701|website=Congress.gov|accessdate=25 January 2018|date=November 23, 1977}}</ref> Honorable Discharge certificates were issued to the former WASP members in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women in the Air Force|url=http://www.aerofiles.com/wafs.html|website=www.aerofiles.com|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> In 1984, each WASP was awarded the [[World War II Victory Medal (United States)|World War II Victory Medal]].<ref name=\"Collins\"/> Those who served for more than one year were also awarded American Theater Ribbon/[[American Campaign Medal]] for their service during the war.<ref name=\"Collins\"/> Many of the medals were accepted by the recipients' sons and daughters on their behalf.<ref name= \"Dromgoole\">{{cite book|last1=Dromgoole|first1=Glenn|title=West Texas Stories|date=2016|publisher=ACU Press|isbn=9780891126744|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3RczDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT65&lpg=PT65&dq=WASP+family+member+accepts+award#v=onepage&q=WASP%20family%20member%20accepts%20award&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe 1977 legislation, either despite or because of its language, did not expressly allow WASPs to be buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. That was because Arlington National Cemetery, unlike most other national cemeteries, is administered by the Department of the Army, not the Department of Veterans Affairs. The Secretary of the Army determines eligibility for Arlington burial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.mil/Funerals/Scheduling-a-Funeral/Establishing-Eligibility|title=Establishing Eligibility|work=Arlington National Cemetery|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Erdrich\"/> The reason for the position taken by the Army on this issue may have been the rapidly diminishing space at Arlington. But in 2002, the Army re-considered and decided that deceased WASPs were able to be buried in Arlington National Cemetery. In 2015, however, the Army re-interpreted the law and its own regulations against the backdrop of thirteen years of war, which once again threatened to deplete the cemetery of land.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/09/07/492954680/female-wwii-pilot-is-finally-laid-to-rest-at-arlington-national-cemetery|title=Female WWII Pilot Is Finally Laid To Rest At Arlington National Cemetery|last=Domonoske|first=Camila|date=September 7, 2016|work=NPR|access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref> The Army ruled that the 1977 statute did not mandate the burial of deceased WASPs at Arlington. When WASP, [[Elaine D. Harmon|Elaine Harmon]], died on April 21, 2015, her request to have her ashes interred at Arlington was denied.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtae.com/article/92-year-old-wasp-florence-shutsy-navigates-political-storm-for-same-rights-as-male-vets/7479520|title=92-year-old WASP, Florence Shutsy, navigates political storm for same rights as male vets|last=Perrine|first=Shannon|date=2016-04-21|website=WTAE|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104004321/https://www.wtae.com/article/92-year-old-wasp-florence-shutsy-navigates-political-storm-for-same-rights-as-male-vets/7479520|archive-date=4 January 2019|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> Another WASP, [[Florence Shutsy-Reynolds]], began a social media campaign to advocate for Harmon and other WASP members who wished to be interred at Arlington.<ref name=\":2\" /> Legislation in 2016 seemingly overruled the Army's interpretation and it was widely reported that WASPs could \"again\" be buried at Arlington.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/21/politics/wwii-female-pilots-arlington-cemetery-irpt/|title=WWII female pilots now can be buried at Arlington|author1=Jareen Imam|author2= CNN|date=May 21, 2016|work=CNN}}</ref> The 2016 law revived the long-held concern about limited space at the cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Gets Bill to Allow Female Pilots' Ashes at Arlington|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/obama-gets-bill-allow-female-pilots-ashes-arlington-n572906|work=NBC News|publisher=Associated Press|date=May 12, 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cotton|first1=Tom|title=Arlington National Cemetery is running out of space. We must act to protect its future.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/tom-cotton-arlington-national-cemetery-is-running-out-of-space-we-must-act-to-protect-its-future/2017/05/26/83f94072-419b-11e7-9869-bac8b446820a_story.html|accessdate=27 January 2018|work=Washington Post|date=26 May 2017}}</ref> Thus, the legislation in the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]] (S.2437 by Sen. [[Barbara Mikulski]] (D-Maryland) and H.R. 4336 by Rep. [[Martha McSally]] (R-Arizona), a retired Air Force fighter pilot), provides only for interment of cremated remains and not ground burial.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Information (Except Text) for H.R.4336 - An act to amend title 38, United States Code, to provide for the inurnment in Arlington National Cemetery of the cremated remains of certain persons whose service has been determined to be active service.|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/4336/all-info|website=Congress.gov|accessdate=27 January 2018|date=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Madge Moore WASP.JPG|thumb|left|[[Madge Moore]] showing the WASP Congressional Gold Medal<ref name=\"Medal\"/> she received in Washington, D.C.]]\nIn 2002 WASP member [[Deanie Bishop Parrish]] with her daughter began plans for a museum dedicated to telling the WASPs story.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tillilie|first1=Stacey|title=Women In The Wings|journal=Baylor Magazine|issue=Winter 2009\u201310|url=https://www.baylor.edu/alumni/magazine/0802/news.php?action=story&story=65594|date=November 30, 2009}}</ref> The hangar building used for the museum, Hangar One, was originally built in 1929 and was part of the Sweetwater Municipal Airport facilities which became Avenger Field.<ref>{{cite news|title=WASP Museum welcomes Ables as new director|url=http://sweetwaterreporter.com/content/wasp-museum-welcomes-ables-new-director|work=sweetwaterreporter.com}}</ref> In 2005 the National WASP WWII Museums grand opening was planned for May 28, 2005, which was the 62 anniversary of the first WASP graduating class.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Andrew|title=13 female pilots to return to Sweetwater for WASP Homecoming 2017|url=http://ktxs.com/archive/13-female-pilots-to-return-to-sweetwater-for-wasp-homecoming-2017|accessdate=27 January 2018|work=KTXS}}</ref> Along with the displays of uniforms, vehicles and other artifacts are several aircraft. These include a [[Boeing-Stearman Model 75]] biplane, a [[Fairchild PT-19]] trainer, a [[Cessna AT-17 Bobcat|UC-78 Bamboo Bomber]] and a [[Vultee BT-13 Valiant]] trainer that was donated in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=WASP Museum Exhibits|url=http://waspmuseum.org/exhibits.html|website=waspmuseum.org|accessdate=27 January 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Restored BT-13 Donated to The National WASP Museum|url=http://warbirdsnews.com/warbirds-news/restored-bt-13-donated-the-national-wasp-museum.html|accessdate=27 January 2018|work=Warbirds News|date=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the WASPs were inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2009, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] and the [[United States Congress]] awarded the WASP the [[Congressional Gold Medal]].<ref name=\"gpo\" /><ref name=\"Medal\">{{cite web|title=WASP Congressional Gold Medal|url=http://wingsacrossamerica.us/bill/|website=wingsacrossamerica.us}}</ref> Three of the roughly 300 surviving WASPs were on hand to witness the event. During the ceremony President Obama said, \"The Women Airforce Service Pilots courageously answered their country's call in a time of need while blazing a trail for the brave women who have given and continue to give so much in service to this nation since. Every American should be grateful for their service, and I am honored to sign this bill to finally give them some of the hard-earned recognition they deserve.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123157228 |title=WASP awarded Congressional Gold Medal for service |publisher=Af.mil |access-date=January 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120717135702/http://www.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123157228 |archivedate=July 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On March 10, 2010, the 300 surviving WASPs came to the US Capitol to accept the Congressional Gold Medal from House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] and other Congressional leaders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100310/ap_on_go_co/us_female_world_war_ii_pilots|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312085716/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100310/ap_on_go_co/us_female_world_war_ii_pilots|url-status=dead|title=Female WWII aviators honored with gold medal|archivedate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> On New Year's Day in 2014 the [[Rose Parade]] featured a float with eight WASP members riding on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailynightly.nbcnews.com/_news/2014/01/01/22124969-cheers-for-wwii-women-pilots-honored-at-rose-parade?lite|title=Cheers for WWII women pilots honored at Rose Parade|author=The Daily Nightly|date=April 13, 2015|work=NBC News}}</ref> It was designed by sculptor [[Don Everhart|Don Everhart II]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Everhart, Don |url=http://doneverhartsculpture.com/united-states-mint/medals/ |title=Congressional Gold Medals Don Everhart II |accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> The medal is on display at the [[Boeing Aviation Hangar]] at the [[Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center]] in Chantilly, Virginia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/congressional-gold-medal-women-airforce-service-pilots |title=Congressional Gold Medal Women Airforce service Pilots |accessdate=May 25, 2019|date=March 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOther aspects of the WASP legacy include the designs and symbols of the WASP organization. Shutsy-Reynolds took over WASP merchandising in 1988 and designed the [[scarf]] that many WASP members wore.<ref name=\":04\"/> She also created unique jewelry based on the WASP wings symbols.<ref name=\":04\" />\n\nThe WASP actively inspired successive generations of women, including aviator, [[Jerrie Cobb]], [[Gulf War|Desert Storm]] pilot, [[Kelly Hamilton]], astronaut, [[Eileen Collins]], and [[Terry London Rinehart]], who was one of the first 10 women to be hired as a [[Airline|commercial airline]] pilot in 1976.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=113}} Colonel [[Kimberly Olsen]] \"credited the WASP for her opportunity to serve her country.\"{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=113}}\n\n==Discrimination==\nWASP members faced [[Sexism|discrimination because of their gender]] during their work numerous times. Some male pilots and commanders were unhappy to have a women's presence in the traditionally male setting of the military.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=113-114}} One WASP, [[Lorraine Rodgers]], later recalled that some men \"refused to acknowledge their ability,\" or that the men didn't trust the smaller women to be able to handle the planes.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} Some commanders would give out \"undesirable\" planes to the WASP to fly.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} One commander at Love Field was eventually formally admonished for treating the women unfairly.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} WASP [[Teresa James]] believed that the women pilots were disliked because they \"flew longer than the men (service pilots). We flew our tails off.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> However, James also reported that she was sometimes \"treated like a celebrity\" when she stopped at Army bases for refueling.<ref name=\":11\" /> She said, \"They had never seen a woman pilot in an Air Force airplane.\"<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27864918/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Pilot Soars With Stars|last=Williams|first=Ernestine|date=1993-05-13|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-31|pages=1D|via=Newspapers.com}} and {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27864733/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Space Would be Pilot's Final Frontier|last=|first=|date=1993-05-13|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2019-01-31|pages=4D|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nCamp Davis at North Carolina had the most prejudice and discrimination against the WASP.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} The base commander, Major Stephenson, told the women that \"both they and the planes were expendable.\"{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} Women at Camp Davis were unfairly evaluated in their flying, according to WASP [[Alia Corbett]].{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} Women were not given practice time, unlike the men.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} [[Sabotage]] was suspected in some incidents at the camp and Cochran found traces of sugar in the engine at one WASP crash site.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} Two WASP women died in the line of duty at Camp Davis.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}} There were fourteen accidents involving improperly maintained towing planes at Camp Davis and planes at Camp Davis were found to be using the wrong octane fuel.{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=135}}\n\nWhile the women were doing the same job as men who were also civilian ferry pilots, the WASP were paid at two-thirds the rate of their male counterparts.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=114}}\n\nThe initial force of the Women's Army Ferrying Service (WAFS) put the cap on the age of recruits at 35 in order \"to avoid the irrationality of women when they enter and go through [[menopause]].\"{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=125}} At the time, the military had determined that age 40 was the time when menopause began, so if the war lasted more than 5 years, most recruits would just be entering the time of \"debilitating irrationality.\"{{Sfn|Monahan|Neidel-Greenlee|2010|p=125}} The WASP were even grounded for a time during their [[menstrual cycle]]s by male commanders because they believed they were \"less efficient during menses.\"{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=115}} This was stopped when flight records showed that this thinking was false.{{Sfn|Cornelsen|2005|p=115}} Some WASP were allowed to choose not to fly during menstruation and the pilots' periods were seen as a form of medical disability by military doctors.{{Sfn|Sage|2017|p=17-18}}\n\nOn the military planes, there weren't facilities for the women to use the bathroom.<ref name=\":8\" /> When women were ferrying the planes, they had to touch down occasionally and women were not allowed to eat in some restaurants because they were wearing pants.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==Notable WASP aviators==\n[[File:Jackiewasptrainees.jpg|thumb|[[Jacqueline Cochran|Jackie Cochran]] (center) with WASP trainees]]\n\n* [[Mildred \"Micky\" Axton|Mildred Darlene \"Micky\" Tuttle Axton]]\n* [[Betty Tackaberry Blake]], the last surviving member of the first WASP training group (Class 43-W-1 at Sweetwater, Texas, graduated April 24, 1943),<ref>{{cite web|title=Betty C.G.T. Blake|url=http://veterantributes.org/TributeDetail.php?recordID=2225|website=Veteran Tributes|publisher=Veteran Tributes, Gulfport, MS|access-date=19 September 2015}}</ref> died April 9, 2015.\n*Doris Bristol<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwii-women-pilots.org/rosters.html|title=WWII WASP Graduates|website=Women Airforce Service Pilots - Remembered By Those who Knew Them|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> (1920-2010), class of 43-W-5\n* Mary S. Reineberg Burchard (1916\u20132012), class of 44-W-6.<ref>Across, Wings. (2012-02-17) [http://waspfinalflight.blogspot.com/2012/02/wasp-mary-reinberg-burchard-44-w-6-jan.html WASP Final Flight: WASP Mary Reinberg Burchard, 44-W-6 Jan. 28, 2012]. Waspfinalflight.blogspot.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n* [[Ann Baumgartner|Ann Baumgartner Carl]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-070323-027.pdf |title=Flying for Freedom |publisher=Nationalmuseum.af.mil |access-date=July 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226112912/http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-070323-027.pdf |archivedate=December 26, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Pearl Laska Chamberlain]]&nbsp;\u2013 First woman to solo a single-engine airplane up the Alaska Highway in 1946.\n* [[Elizabeth Chambers (pilot)|Elizabeth \"Betty\" Maxine Chambers]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prologue.blogs.archives.gov/2014/12/20/a-wasps-story/|title=A WASP's Story|last=hilaryparkinson|date=2014-12-20|website=Prologue: Pieces of History|access-date=2016-10-22}}</ref>\n* [[Jacqueline Cochran]]&nbsp;\u2013 Director of the WASP. In 1938, Cochran became famous nationwide for winning the Bendix Transcontinental Race\n*[[Gwendolyne Cowart]]\n* [[Violet Cowden]]\n* [[Rosa Charlyne Creger]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wingsacrossamerica.us/web/creger.htm |title=Charlyne Creger, WASP |publisher=Wingsacrossamerica.us |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Nancy Batson Crews]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=1526 |title=Factsheets : Unknown Fact Sheet |publisher=Nationalmuseum.af.mil |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Selma Cronan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/selma.html|title=Selma Cronan|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|access-date=March 13, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Nancye Ruth Lowe Crout]], (Class 43-W-4),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twu.edu/library/wasp/wasppdf/Crout.pdf|title=Nancye Ruth Lowe Crout |work=Texas Woman's University WASP}}</ref> died January 21, 2016.\n* [[Iris Cummings]]\n* [[Jeanne P. d'Ambly]]&nbsp;\u2013 member of the 43-W-5 class<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twu.edu/library/wasp/wasppdf/DAmbley.pdf|title=Jeanne Perot D'Ambley|work=Texas Woman's University WASP}}</ref>\n* [[Cornelia Fort]]&nbsp;\u2013 One of the original WAFS. Fort's experience included evading attacking [[Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service|IJNAS]] carrier planes at Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941. She became the first WAFS fatality in a midair collision while flying a BT-13 near [[Merkel, Texas]] on March 23, 1943.\n* [[Elizabeth L. Gardner]] of Rockford, Illinois<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docsteach.org/documents/document/elizabeth-gardner|title=Women's Airforce Service Pilot Elizabeth L. Gardner &#124; DocsTeach|website=www.docsteach.org}}</ref>\n* [[Maggie Gee (pilot)|Maggie Gee]]&nbsp;\u2013 One of only two Asian-Americans (Chinese) in the WASP, the other being Hazel Ying Lee.\n[[File:Group of Women Airforce Service Pilots and B-17 Flying Fortress.jpg|thumb|Frances Green, Margaret (Peg) Kirchner, Ann Waldner and Blanche Osborn leaving their plane, \"Pistol Packin' Mama\"]]\n* [[Betty Gillies]]\n* [[Ann Warren Griffith]], writer, wrote about her WASP experiences in ''The New Yorker''\n* [[Betty Haas Pfister]]\n* Lois Hailey<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwii-women-pilots.org/lbhailey43-3/lbhailey.html |title=Lois E. Hailey&nbsp;\u2013 An Aviatrix from WWII |publisher=Wwii-women-pilots.org |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Elaine D. Harmon]], first WASP aviator interred at [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n* [[Sara Payne Hayden]]\n* [[Bernice Falk Haydu]]\n* [[Gloria Heath]]<ref>Briggs, John. [http://wingsacrossamerica.us/records_all/wasp_articles/heath.pdf A Singular Woman.] ''Greenwich.'' July/August 1999.</ref>\n* [[Jean Hixson]]\n* [[Carla Horowitz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twudigital.cdmhost.com/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/p214coll2&CISOPTR=3768&CISOBOX=1&REC=1 |title=Digital Collections : Item Viewer |publisher=Twudigital.cdmhost.com |date=February 7, 2005 |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Evelyn Greenblatt Howren]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Evelyn Greenblatt, WASP |url=http://www.wingsacrossamerica.us/web/howren.html | date=February 13, 2008 | website=WASP on the Web |publisher=Wings Across America | access-date=December 12, 2018 | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414152159/http://www.wingsacrossamerica.us/web/howren.html | archive-date=April 14, 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Celia Hunter]]\n* [[Marge Hurlburt]]&nbsp;\u2013 She was named to the Board of Directors of the Professional Race Pilots Association to represent the interests of female pilots and held the woman's international airspeed record at the time her death in July 1947. Marge died while performing as part of a [[Barnstorming|flying circus]] that she joined to raise money to build a new racing airplane.<ref>{{cite web| vauthors =| title = Marge Hurlburt Is Killed While Stunting In Air Show| publisher = St. Petersburg Times| date = July 5, 1947| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ib0KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=304DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6109,1451195&dq=airshow+crash| access-date =July 12, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.gazettenews.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2318:medal-for-marge-finds-home-at-iwasm&catid=70:columns&Itemid=395|title = 'Medal for Marge' finds home at IWASM&nbsp;...|date = 16 March 2011|access-date = 30 September 2015|website = |publisher = Gazette News Online|last = Moore|first = Rose}}</ref>\n* Janet Hutchinson&nbsp;\u2013 of the [[Flying Hutchinsons]], joined at age 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wings1944.blogspot.com.au/2009/11/famous-pilot-tells-ju-aviation-students.html |title = Famous pilot tells JU aviation students about her live in the clouds. |access-date=May 2, 2012|date = November 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Teresa James]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=1553 |title=Factsheets : Unknown Fact Sheet |publisher=Nationalmuseum.af.mil |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Marguerite \"Ty\" Hughes Killen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://waspfinalflight.blogspot.com/2011/01/wasp-marguerite-ty-hughes-killen-44-w-8.html|title=WASP Marguerite Ty Hughes Killen, 44-W-8\n|last=Parrish|first=Nancy|date=23 January 2011|access-date=11 August 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Hazel Ying Lee]]&nbsp;\u2013 One of two Asian-Americans (Chinese) in the WASP, the other being Maggie Gee. Lee was the last WASP member to die while serving in program.\n* [[Dorothy Swain Lewis]]&nbsp;\u2013 Worked at [[Piper Aircraft]] Lockhaven, Pennsylvania, Graduate of [[Phoebe Omlie]]'s Tennessee Bureau of Aeronautics Women Aviation Instructor Program in Nashville TN (Feb 1943), Instructed Navy pilots V-5 program classes 43F, W3G, W3H, Instructed WASP classes 43-W8,44-W2,44-W4, joined WASP in class 44-W7&5, towed targets in B-26, engineering flights various other aircraft, sculpted WASP trainee statue on [[United States Air Force Academy]] Honor Court, Colorado Springs, painted official portrait<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/ag/aghistpage.php?id=77 |title=Official Page of Janet Reno|access-date=March 16, 2013}}</ref> of [[Janet Reno]] for US Department of Justice\n* [[Doris Lockness]]<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times&nbsp;\u2013 February 11, 2017&nbsp;\u2013 Doris Lockness, one of the country's most honored female pilots, dies at 106\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-doris-lockness-20170208-story.html|title=Doris Lockness, one of the country's most honored female pilots, dies at 106|date=February 11, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=11 February 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Barbara Erickson London]]&nbsp;\u2013 The only WASP member to be awarded the [[Air Medal]] during World War II.<ref>{{cite web| vauthors =| title = Barbara Erickson London| work = Fact Sheets| publisher = National Museum of the Air Force| url = http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=1539| access-date =July 15, 2009 }}</ref> Following the war, medals were awarded to other WASP members.\n* [[Grace Lotowycz|Grace Elizabeth \"Betty\" Ashwell Lotowycz]] 44-W-7\n* [[Nancy Love]]\n* [[Iola \"Nancy\" Clay Magruder]] A member of class 44-W-7, her orders sent her to Enid, Oklahoma where she flew BT-13, BT-15, AT-6, PT-17, and B-18.\n*[[Madge Moore]]<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://operationfifinella.org/2016/12/27/madge-moore-44-4/|title=Madge Moore 44-4|last=Nagle|first=Bobbi|date=27 December 2016|website=Operation Fifinella|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301195719/https://operationfifinella.org/2016/12/27/madge-moore-44-4/|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n* Annabelle Craft Moss&nbsp;\u2013 Moss flew the AT-6 Trainer, and was responsible for transporting officers from base to base.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Michael Riley| title = Colorado women honored with the Congressional Gold Medal| work = [[The Denver Post]]| access-date = 2012-10-09| date = 2010-03-11| url = http://www.denverpost.com/frontpage/ci_14652184}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Grand Junction honored for service as World War II pilot| work = Wings and WASP| access-date = 2012-10-09| date = 2010-04-18| url = http://wings1944.blogspot.com/2010/04/grand-junction-honored-for-service-as.html}}</ref>\n* [[Anne Noggle]]&nbsp;\u2013 Following the war she became a noted photographer and writer. She took the photos for ''For God, Country and the Thrill of It: Women Airforce Pilots of World War II'', with an introduction by [[Dora Dougherty Strother]].<ref>{{cite web| vauthors =| title = Anne Noggle WASP 44-W-1| work = Wings Across America| date = August 23, 2005| url = http://wingsacrossamerica.us/web/noggle_anne.htm| access-date =July 15, 2009 }}\n</ref>\n*[[Dorothy Olsen]]\n* [[Lorrie Otto]]\n* [[Deanie Bishop Parrish]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wingsacrossamerica.us/deanie.htm |title=WASP Deanie Bishop Parrish |publisher=Wingsacrossamerica.us |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wings1944.blogspot.com/2012/07/maggie-kennons-interiew-with-wasp.html|title=WINGS AND WASP: Maggie Kennon's interview with a WASP!|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Suzanne Parish|Suzanne Upjohn DeLano Parish]], co-founder of Kalamazoo Air Museum, later called the [[Air Zoo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airzoo.org/page.php?page_id=111|title=Sue Parish |publisher=Air Zoo of Kalamazoo, Michigan|access-date=September 13, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Vilma Lazar Qualls]] (May 5, 1917&nbsp;\u2013 November 2, 2003) A member of class 43-W-3, she was assigned to Long Beach Army Airbase after training. She flew BT-13, C-47, B-17 and B-24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twu.edu/library/wasp/wasppdf/Qualls.pdf |title=Women Airforce Service Pilots |publisher=Texas Woman's University}}</ref>\n* [[Hazel Jane Raines]]\n* [[Mabel Rawlinson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everydaycitizen.com/2007/05/my_aunt_mabel_my_hero.html |title=Fallen Hero: Fly Girl from Kalamazoo |publisher=Everyday Citizen |date=May 28, 2007 |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:WASPs on flight line at Laredo AAF.jpg|thumb|WASP members on the flight line at [[Laredo Army Air Field]], Texas, January 22, 1944]]\n* [[Katherine Rawls]]\n* [[Ola Mildred Rexroat]], An [[Oglala|Oglala Sioux]] from Pine Ridge Indian Reservation, South Dakota, was the only Native American woman in the WASP.<ref name=\"Defense.gov\" />\n* [[Mary Anne Richey]]\n* [[Margaret Ringenberg]]\n* [[Lorraine Rodgers]]\n* [[Dawn Seymour]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twu.edu/wasp/Seymour.pdf|title=Dawn Rochow Seymour|website=Women Airforce Service Pilots|publisher=Texas Women's University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040115180915/http://twu.edu/wasp/Seymour.pdf|archive-date=15 January 2004|url-status=|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Evelyn Genevieve Sharp|Evelyn Sharp]]&nbsp;\u2013 In 1938, Evelyn Sharp was the youngest person in the United States to receive a commercial pilot license.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aero.state.ne.us/Sharp.htm|title=Evelyn Sharp|work=Nebraska Aviation Hall of Fame|publisher=Nebraska.gov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308155604/http://www.aero.nebraska.gov/Sharp.htm|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Florence Shutsy-Reynolds]] (1923-2018)&nbsp;\u2013 earned her pilot's license in 1941, just before women were barred from the government-operated training program at local airports due to the expected need of more male pilots. Following the death of her husband around 1988, she took over the WASP organization's \"Stores\" job, making and selling intricate silver and bronze jewelry, banners, scarves and other WASP-themed items.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20021111waspreg2p2.asp|title=Fayette Woman Tells Story of Females Flying on the WWII Home Front|last=Lash|first=Cindi|date=11 November 2002|work=Post-Gazette|access-date=19 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104072802/http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20021111waspreg2p2.asp|archive-date=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Gertrude Tompkins Silver]]&nbsp;\u2013 The only WASP member to go missing during World War II. She departed from Mines Field (currently LAX) for Palm Springs, on October 26, 1944, flying a P-51D Mustang destined for New Jersey but never arrived. In January 2010 search efforts to locate the possible crash site in [[Santa Monica Bay]] were unsuccessful.<ref>[http://www.aircraftwrecks.com/gts/gts.htm Ongoing Search For Mrs. Gertrude Tompkins Silver.] ''Aircraft Wrecks in the Mountains and Deserts of the American West.''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scubadiving.com/news/2009/09/search-underway-for-missing-heroine-of-world-war-ii-and-her-p-51-mustang |title=Search Underway for Missing Heroine of World War II and her P-51 Mustang &#124; Scuba Diving Magazine |publisher=Scubadiving.com |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ure|first1=James W.|title=Siezed {{sic}} by the Sun: The Life and Disappearance of World War II Pilot Gertrude Tompkins|year=2017|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-1613735879}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Last Missing WASP of WWII|url=https://adventuresinrediscovery.com/2013/08/30/the-last-missing-wasp-of-wwii/|website=Adventures in Rediscovery|accessdate=28 January 2018|date=30 August 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Helen Wyatt Snapp]]\n* [[Jane Straughan]], graduate of class 43-W-1.\n* [[Elizabeth Strohfus]]&nbsp;\u2013 flew [[Martin B-26 Marauder|B-26 Widowmakers]] and pulled 6 G's in a F-16 at age 72.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2009/08/12/wasps|title=65 years later, female WWII test pilots finally recognized|last=Baran|first=Madeleine|last2=Tundel|first2=Nikki|date=August 13, 2009|work=MPR News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923121625/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2009/08/12/wasps|archive-date=23 January 2018|url-status=|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref> She died at 96 on March 6, 2016, in Faribault, MN.<ref name=\"MST\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-wwii-era-pilot-elizabeth-strohfus-dies-at-96/371319891/|title=Minnesota WWII-era pilot Elizabeth Strohfus dies at 96|work=Star Tribune|access-date=March 8, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308063303/http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-wwii-era-pilot-elizabeth-strohfus-dies-at-96/371319891/|archivedate=March 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"TWP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/elizabeth-strohfus-world-war-ii-era-pilot-dies-at-96/2016/03/08/b0352e08-e553-11e5-b0fd-073d5930a7b7_story.html|title=Elizabeth Strohfus, World War II-era pilot, dies at 96|date=March 8, 2016|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 9, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Dora Dougherty Strother]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=1536 |title=Factsheets : Unknown Fact Sheet |publisher=Nationalmuseum.af.mil |access-date=July 10, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Coon Walters]]\n* [[Florene Miller Watson]]\u2014one of the first WAFS volunteers.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amarillo.com/article/20140209/OBITUARIES/302099839|title=Florene Miller Watson|date=9 February 2014|website=Amarillo Globe|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811045842/http://amarillo.com/obituaries/2014-02-08/florene-miller-watson|archive-date=11 August 2014|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wai.org/pioneers/2005/florene-miller-watson|title=Florene Miller Watson|website=Women in Aviation International|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102035535/https://www.wai.org/pioneers/2005/florene-miller-watson|archive-date=2 January 2019|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref>\n* [[Betty Jane Williams]]\u2014went on to become a Lt Colonel in her later military career.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/support/wall-of-honor/ltcol-b-j-williams-usaf-ret|title=LtCol B J Williams USAF (Ret)|date=2016-01-16|website=National Air and Space Museum|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103185649/https://airandspace.si.edu/support/wall-of-honor/ltcol-b-j-williams-usaf-ret|archive-date=3 January 2019|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref>\n* [[Mary E. Williamson]] (1924\u20132012)<ref>Finding aid for the Mary Ellen Williamson Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP) Collection, Archives and Special Collections, Dr. C.C. and Mabel L. Criss Library, University of Nebraska at Omaha. ([http://unomaha-public.lyrasistechnology.org/repositories/4/resources/392 online])</ref>\n* [[Ginny Wood]]\n* [[Marty Wyall]] - was part of the last class of WASP in 1944. She later became the WASP historian.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://twudigital.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p214coll2/id/5153|title=Mary Anna Martin Wyall, class of 44-W-10: letters 1944-1945 :: Women Airforce Service Pilots|date=1994|editor-last=Durr|editor-first=Nancy Marshall|website=Texas Women's University, Special Collections|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries and fictional depictions==\n* In the 1943 movie ''[[A Guy Named Joe]]'', Pete Sandidge (Spencer Tracy) is the reckless pilot of a North American B-25 Mitchell bomber flying out of England during World War II. He is in love with Women Airforce Service Pilot Dorinda Durston (Irene Dunne), a civilian pilot ferrying aircraft across the Atlantic.\n* ''[[Ladies Courageous]]'' a 1944 film starring [[Loretta Young]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20197214/madge-ragan-leon-and-role-as-a-wasp/|title=Daughter of Leon Theater Owner Was in Air Service|date=1945-08-20|work=The Amarillo Globe-Times|access-date=2020-03-01|url-status=live|pages=7|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* Season 1, Episode 22 of [[Baa Baa Black Sheep (TV series)|Baa Baa Black Sheep]] was entitled W*A*S*P*S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0517392/|title=\"Black Sheep Squadron\" W*A*S*P*S (TV Episode 1977)|work=IMDb}}</ref> It first aired on March 1, 1977. The episode has several errors of fact. Two are that there is no \"s\" at the end of the name, because the name itself is plural and the WASP never flew overseas.\n* The novel ''Skies Over Sweetwater'' by Julia Moberg is entirely about WASP and follows the lives of fictional characters as they train.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moberg|first1=Julia|title=Skies Over Sweetwater|url=http://juliamoberg.com/skies-over-sweetwater/|website=juliamoberg.com|publisher=Julia Moberg|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n* In the modern ''[[Wonder Woman]]'' continuity, [[Steve Trevor]]'s mother, Diana Trevor, was a WASP who inadvertently crash-landed on [[Themyscira (DC Comics)|Themyscira]] on a mission in the 1940s and died helping the Amazons fight an attacking menace.\n* A documentary produced by Ken Magid, ''Women of Courage,'' was shown on PBS in 1993.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* In 2000 novel ''Queen of Aces'' by Aaron Masters: an action adventure story about one of America's greatest pilots, Meg Reilly, as told first-hand by ''Aviation Life'' reporter Aaron Masters. Meg follows in the footsteps of her godmother Amelia Earhart and father Rye Reilly, a WWI MOH awardee, combat ace, and aircraft designer. Mock combat barnstormer and Bendix racer Meg soon becomes \"First Lady of the Air\" with the death of Amelia. With the outbreak of WWII, Meg is relegated to ferrying duty, first with the WAFS and later as a WASP, while her brothers become combat pilots. Meg makes a major contribution to the war only to be deactivated along with her fellow WASPs in 1944. Meg ventures to England with three other WASPs to conduct transition training on the new P-51D. Soon, the foursome is asked to secretly ferry these much-needed Mustangs to a forward base in France. On one particular mission, a vicious twist of fate thrusts her into combat\u2014the first American woman ever to engage the enemy in hostile skies. (Top Publications, Dallas, TX). Note \u2013 Soon to be a movie by the same name (Silver Lion Films).{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n* The 2008 TV movie ''Warbirds'' features a WASP [[Boeing B-29|B-29]] crew, whose plane is commandeered for a secret mission but crashes on a [[pteranodon]]-infested island.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=1047544|title=Warbirds}}</ref>\n* A 2009 episode of the TV show ''[[Cold Case (TV series)|Cold Case]]'' features the investigators looking for the murderer of a WASP, after her plane is found in modern-day Philadelphia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1506593/|title=\"Cold Case\" WASP (TV Episode 2009)|author=jotix100|date=November 30, 2009|work=IMDb}}</ref>\n* In the 2012 ''[[Captain Marvel (Marvel Comics)|Captain Marvel]]'' story from Marvel comics, [[Carol Danvers]] travels through time to 1943 where she fights alongside a squad of Women Airforce Service Pilots on an island off the coast of Peru.<ref>[http://uk.ign.com/articles/2012/10/02/captain-marvel-4-post-game-with-kelly-sue-deconnick Captain Marvel #4 Post-Game with Kelly Sue DeConnick&nbsp;\u2013 IGN]. Uk.ign.com (2012-10-02). Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n* The 2010 novel \"Fly Girl\" by Sherri L Smith tells the story of Ida-Mae \"Jonesy\" Jones, a poor African American woman who dreams of becoming a pilot. She joins the WASP and serves until the war's end.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Flygirl-Sherri-L-Smith/dp/0142417254 Flygirl: Sherri L. Smith: 9780142417256: Amazon.com: Books]. Amazon.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n* The 2013 novel \"The All-Girl Filling Station's Last Reunion\" tells the story of Fritzi and her sisters who helped out during the war by running their father's filling station and later flew with the WASPs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1400065941/|title=The All-Girl Filling Station's Last Reunion: A Novel: Fannie Flagg: 9781400065943: Amazon.com: Books|work=amazon.com}}</ref>\n* The 2010 novel \"Silver Wings\" by H.P. Munro tells the story of 6 women training at Avenger Field and their subsequent deployments. The story centers on Lily and Helen who meet and fall in love during their training.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1482023571/|title=Silver Wings: H. P. Munro: 9781482023572: Amazon.com: Books|work=amazon.com}}</ref>\n* The 2010 historical novel \"The Last Jump\" relates the story of how male pilots of the top secret 509th Composite Group (who eventually dropped two atomic bombs) were \"shamed\" into flying the B-29 bomber by having WASP flyers deliver the first plane to Wendover AFB, Utah. CO Col. Paul Tibbets orchestrated the entire episode when he found out his \"best pilots\" were afraid to fly the \"widowmaker\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1432756656/|title=Amazon.com: The Last Jump: A Novel of World War II (9781432756659): John E. Nevola: Books|work=amazon.com}}</ref>\n* Season 3, Episode 15 of \"Army Wives\" is a flashback episode that mentions the WASP pilots from WWII.\n* Meredith Dayna Levy wrote a play called 'Decision Height' which tells the story of six WASP trainees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kcactf4.org/2014/02/decision-height-demonstrates-that-girl-power-never-gets-old/|title='Decision Height' Demonstrates that Girl Power Never Gets Old}}</ref>\n* Dallas playwright Rusty Harding wrote a play entitled 'Fly Babies\", a fictionalized story based on the WASPs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hitplays.com/default.aspx?pg=sd&st=FLY+BABIES&p=20462/|title=Heuer Publishing - FLY BABIES|website=www.hitplays.com}}</ref> Yes \n*The Flight Girls, a novel by Noelle Salazar, was inspired by the civilian women pilots who flew military planes during World War 2.\n* \"Betty Wall: Girls Don't Fly\" (2015) Documentary by Steve Cloutier, is an intimate portrait of how one irrepressible, small-town girl became a flyer with the Women\u2019s Airforce Service Pilots, aka WASP. \u201cGirls Don\u2019t Fly\u201d is a testament to the struggles and victories faced by this little-known group of \u201cThe Greatest Generation\u201d- as told by one of the women who lived it.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Betsy Ross Air Corps]]\n* [[Night Witches]] (588th Night Bomber Regiment&nbsp;\u2013 Soviet)\n* [[Air Transport Auxiliary]] (ATA&nbsp;\u2013 British)\n* [[Royal Canadian Air Force Women's Division]] (RCAFWD)\n* [[Women Airforce Service Pilots Badge]]\n* [[Women in the Air Force (WAF)]]\n* [[Women's Army Corps]] (WAC)\n* [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force]] (WAAF&nbsp;\u2013 British)\n* [[Women's Auxiliary Australian Air Force]] (WAAAF)\n* [[Women in aviation]]\n* [[Timeline of women in aviation]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* Clark, Marie Mountain. ''Dear Mother and Daddy: World War II Letters Home from a WASP''. Livonia Michigan: First Page Publications, 2005. {{ISBN|1-928623-63-8}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Cole|first=Jean Hascall|title=Women Pilots of World War II|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|publisher=University of Utah Press|date=1992|isbn=978-0-87480-493-5|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=od6hmG43CesC&lpg=PR18&dq=WASP%20Troop%20Carrier%20Command.&pg=PR18#v=onepage&q=WASP%20Troop%20Carrier%20Command.&f=false}}.\n* {{cite journal|last=Cornelsen|first=Kathleen|title=Women Airforce Service Pilots of World War II: Exploring Military Aviation, Encountering Discrimination, and Exchanging Traditional Roles in Service to America|journal=Journal of Women's History |volume=17|issue=4|date=2005|pages=111\u2013119|ref=harv |doi=10.1353/jowh.2005.0046|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/4b9fd1b4cf051b127c3dfff7c51f6d74928eefb9}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Dubois|first1=Ellen Carol|first2=Lynn|last2=Dumenil|chapter=Women in the Military|title=Through Women's Eyes|location=Boston|publisher=St. Martin's|year=2012|isbn=978-0-312-67607-0|ref=harv|edition=3rd}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Granger|first=Byrd Howell|title=On Final Approach: The Women Airforce Service Pilots of W.W.II|location=New York|publisher=Falconer Publishing Co.|date=1991|isbn=978-0-9626267-0-8|ref=harv}}.\n* Haynsworth, Leslie and David Toomey. ''Amelia Earhart's Daughters''. New York: William Morrow and Company, 1998. {{ISBN|978-0-688-15233-8}}.\n* Keil, Sally Van Wagenen, ''Those Wonderful Women in Their Flying Machines: The Unknown Heroines of World War II''. New York: Four Directions Press, 1990. {{ISBN|0-9627659-0-2}}.\n* LoPinto, Winnie, ''I was a Woman Pilot in 1945''. Sheffield, UK: Green Leaf Publishing, 2001. {{ISBN|978-1-4912-83